<!-- The test suite's logging voice. Logback prefers logback-test.xml over
     logback.xml wherever both are on the classpath, so this file shadows
     resources/logback.xml for `clojure -X:test` and nothing else — the
     production config is untouched.

     Most of what the suite printed was DELIBERATE: it starts and stops http
     servers, rejects malformed aircraft, and refuses SSE clients on purpose,
     and every one of those announced itself at INFO or WARN. That is the
     expected output of a PASSING test, and it drowned the one line that
     matters — the failure.

     The level stays at INFO and the CONSOLE is filtered instead. That
     distinction is load-bearing, not fussiness: tools.logging asks the logger
     `enabled?` BEFORE it calls log*, so lowering the root level to ERROR does
     not merely hide a warning — it stops the call from happening at all, and
     the tests that assert on what was logged by redefining log* (coerce-test,
     receiver-test) see nothing and fail. Filtering at the appender leaves
     every log call firing exactly as it does in production and only declines
     to print it. What still reaches the terminal is ERROR and above.

     TWO LOGGERS ARE SILENCED OUTRIGHT, because the suite provokes their errors
     ON PURPOSE and each arrives with a full stack trace:

       adsb.http.routes  routes-test throws `secret internal detail` at the
                         handler to prove the error response does NOT leak it.
                         The log line is the throw being caught, i.e. the test
                         passing.
       adsb.ingest.poll  poll-test hands the poll loop a callback that throws
                         `boom`, to prove one bad batch does not kill the loop.
                         It retries, so it logs four times.

     Named rather than levelled away: every OTHER logger still prints at ERROR,
     so an exception from code the suite did not deliberately break is still
     news. Neither of these two is among the namespaces whose logging is
     asserted on (coerce, receiver), so switching them off costs no coverage —
     and the tests above assert on the RESPONSE and the LOOP, never on the log. -->
<configuration>
  <appender name="console" class="ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender">
    <filter class="ch.qos.logback.classic.filter.ThresholdFilter">
      <level>ERROR</level>
    </filter>
    <encoder>
      <pattern>%d{HH:mm:ss.SSS} %-5level %logger{24} - %msg%n</pattern>
    </encoder>
  </appender>

  <logger name="adsb.http.routes" level="OFF"/>
  <logger name="adsb.ingest.poll" level="OFF"/>

  <root level="INFO">
    <appender-ref ref="console"/>
  </root>
</configuration>
